<span class="displaytext"><b>for immediate release<br/>contact:</b> (candidate last) press shop (857) 288-6390 <p align="center"> <b>(candidate last)'s increasingly "fuzzy" stats</b> </p><p><b> <u>(candidate last) falsely claims that "violent crime" went up in massachusetts:</u> </b> </p><p><b>yesterday, (candidate last) falsely claimed that "violent crime" went up in massachusetts.</b> "'gov. (candidate last) did not have a good record in dealing with violent crime.' (candidate last) pulled a sheet of paper out of his pocket that listed fbi crime statistics for massachusetts while (candidate last) was governor. murders were up 7.5 percent, robbery was up 12 percent, he said. <u>'he had an increase in murder and violent crime while he was governor,'</u> (candidate last) said. 'so it's not so much the isolated situation which he and the judge will have to explain _ he's kind of thrown her under the bus, so it's hard to know how this is all going to come out. but the reality is, he did not have a record of reducing violent crime.'" (charles babington, "(candidate last) calls on judge he appointed to resign after washington state murders," <em>the associated press</em>, 11/24/07) </p><p><b> <u>fact: according to the fbi statistics, overall "violent crime" decreased in massachusetts under governor (candidate last):</u> </b> </p><p><em>under governor (candidate last), the violent crime rate in massachusetts decreased by over 7%. the violent crime rate was lower than the national average. prior to governor (candidate last), the violent crime rate was increasing. <br/></em> <br/> </p><p><b> <u>fact: according to fbi statistics, the overall crime rate decreased in massachusetts under governor (candidate last):</u> </b> </p><p><b>under governor (candidate last), the overall crime rate fell by 8% over his four years in office.</b> "car thefts and larcenies also were down, in line with national trends, and helped contribute to an overall 8 percent decline in crime during (candidate last)'s four years, according to the fbi stats." (dave wedge, "crime up during (candidate last) tenure," <em>the boston herald</em>, 9/26/07) </p><p><b> <u>fact: according to fbi statistics, other crimes were down under governor (candidate last) (2002-2006):</u> </b> </p><p><b>- assaults down 15%.</b> (fbi crime in the united states website, http://www.fbi.gov/ucr, accessed 10/12/07) </p><p><b>- rape down 2%.</b> (fbi crime in the united states website, http://www.fbi.gov/ucr, accessed 10/12/07) </p><p><b>- larceny/theft down 6%.</b> (fbi crime in the united states website, http://www.fbi.gov/ucr, accessed 10/12/07) </p><p><b>- motor vehicle theft down 32%.</b> (fbi crime in the united states website, http://www.fbi.gov/ucr, accessed 10/12/07) </p><p><b> <u>fact: this isn't the first time (candidate last) has used "fuzzy ... math":</u> </b> </p><p><b>abc news: (candidate last) uses "fuzzy healthcare math" in radio ad.</b> "to hear (candidate full) describe it in his new radio ad, the british medical system is a scary place. 'my chance of surviving prostate cancer – and thank god i was cured of it – in the united states: 82 percent,' (candidate last) says in a new radio spot airing in new hampshire. 'my chances of surviving prostate cancer in england: only 44 percent, under socialized medicine.' but the data (candidate last) cites comes from a single study published eight years ago by a not-for-profit group, and is contradicted by official data from the british government. according to the united kingdom's office for national statistics, for men diagnosed with prostate cancer between 1999 and 2003, the 'five-year survival rate' – a common measurement in cancer statistics – was 74.4 percent." (rick klein, "rudy's fuzzy healthcare math," abc news, 10/29/07) </p><p><b>the annenberg public policy center: (candidate last) wrongly claims he left a budget surplus.</b> "(candidate last)'s radio ad also asserts that he 'turned a 2.3 billion deficit into a multibillion-dollar surplus' in new york. <u>well, not if you're comparing what he inherited with what he left, which would be a logical way to look at it.</u> when he took office in 1994, (candidate last) was indeed facing a $2.3 billion deficit for the next fiscal year. but (candidate last)'s last budget, issued in may 2001 – before 9/11 – for fiscal 2002, projected a deficit of nearly $2.8 billion in fiscal 2003, the first budget year the new mayor would face. the ibo estimated the deficit would be even larger, about $3.3 billion." ("(candidate last)'s tax puffery," factcheck.org website, <a href="http://www.factcheck.org/elections-2008/(candidate last)s_tax_puffery.html">http://www.factcheck.org/</a>, 7/27/07) </p><p><b> <em>the washington times</em>: (candidate last) exaggerates tax cutting number.</b> "mr. (candidate last) repeated his claim that he 'cut taxes 23 times when i was mayor of new york.' it turns out that many of those cuts were instigated by (PARTY NAME) gov. george pataki and the state legislature. one of several glaring flaws in mr. (candidate last)'s record on taxes was, as the club for growth says, his 1994 'opposition to (PARTY NAME) [gubernatorial] candidate george pataki's proposed cut in the state income tax,' whose rates were among the highest in the country." (editorial, "(candidate last) and (candidate last)," <em>the washington times</em>, 10/14/07)</p></span>



